\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter 4 presented seasonal composites of fire weather variables.
 These composites link climate to extreme bushfire occurrences in Victoria.
 This analysis reflects average—large-scale—climate patterns associated
 with bushfire activity.
 The composites showed anomalies with consistent features from spring—September-
October-November—to summer—December-January-February—.
 Overall, the anomalies are moderate to strong in Victoria and the Tropical
 Pacific Ocean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this chapter is to complement the investigation of average spatial
 patterns.
 Chapter 5 investigates the long-term interannual variability of seasonal
 fire weather in Victoria.
 Fire weather was investigated using seasonal metrics of the McArthur Forest
 Fire Danger Index.
 This index quantifies bushfire danger using meteorological data.
 Additionally, this chapter proposes an alternative bushfire index: “Victorian
 Seasonal Bushfire Index” (VSBI).
 This index is build upon the anomalous areas found in chapter 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, this chapter explores the capability of the VSBI to forecast fire
 weather and activity.
 The investigation required four groups of data: bushfire activity records,
 climate variables, fire weather metrics and climate indices.
 Each group of data comprises several variables that were linearly correlated
 for spring, summer and from spring to summer.
 Using weather station data, the VSBI shows a strong forecasting skill and
 consistent climate-bushfire relationships.
 In the other hand, results using Twentieth Century reanalysis data for
 the Victorian region show its limitations to capture these relationships.
 
\end_layout

