\begin_layout Subsubsection
Original seasonal FFDI computation (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI computed with WS data depict more extreme fire weather for Victoria
 than the calculation using the 20CR.
 This difference is likely to occur for several reasons.
 FFDI variables from renalysis data do not correspond exactly to surface
 values.
 Near-surface reanalysis data was available at the 1000 h-Pa level.
 Calculations using these data do not exactly represent surface level conditions.
 Additionally, the FFDI computed with weather station data use values at
 3 pm.
 Yet, reanalysis data for FFDI variables is available at 6-hourly intervals.
 These intervals limited the availability of data to 4 pm values.
 Moreover, there are intrinsic limitations in the reanalysis dataset already
 discussed in Chapter 2.
 The linear scaling techniques adjusted the biases without significantly
 altering the correlations.
 However, the fire weather variability could change if we use a different
 index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative index might show a different seasonal fire weather trend.
 Yet, the difference is unlikely to be significant.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dowdy2009"

\end_inset

 determined that the FFDI could be comparable to the Canadian Fire Weather
 Index (FWI).
 The study compared the two indices for Australian conditions.
 The FWI is an internationally recognized fire weather index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanWagner1974,VanWagner2005,Dowdy2009a"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the FFDI can be representative of fire weather conditions in
 Victoria.
 Nevertheless, the use of only one realization of the 20CR leaves non-quantified
 uncertainties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 20CR reanalysis has 56 model realizations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Every realization represents an equally possible state of the atmosphere
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, fire weather computed with a mean value realization has a degree
 of uncertainty.
 This uncertainty could be quantified.
 Thus, the bias-correction results are only valid for one possible state
 of the atmosphere.
 However, the seasonal fire weather computations show an increasing trend
 consistent with an atmosphere under a global warming process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stocker2013"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The increasing trend in seasonal fire weather computations for Victoria
 agrees with the results of other investigations for southeastern Australia
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2007,Hennessy2005,Hasson2009"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, climate change is extending the bushfire season in this region
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clarke2011"

\end_inset

.
 However, the available data bases showed that most bushfires occur during
 DJF.
 Therefore, in this investigation the fire season was defined as the season
 December-January-February.
 The results can change—although not significantly- if the bushfire season
 is extended (e.g.
 November-December-January-February-March—).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bias-correction of fire weather variables (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every fire weather variable showed a significant correlation between weather
 station and 20CR data.
 Temperature, relative humidity and wind speed presented a similar variability
 with differences in magnitude.
 The application of linear scaling techniques corrected the mean of these
 three variables.
 The results were satisfactory since the correlations did not significantly
 change—and in some cases even improved—.Additionally, the bias-correction
 of reanalysis data produced similar outcomes in magnitude.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although, the bias-correction process yielded satisfactory results, weather
 station data was not homogenized.
 This is a limitation that is particularly evident for wind speed.
 The seasonal values for this variable show an abrupt increase after the
 year 2000.
 The change in the technology to measure the variable might cause the inhomogene
ities.
 On the other hand, linear scaling techniques did not correct biases in
 precipitation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 20CR data does not accurately represents precipitation in Victoria.
 The linear scaling bias-correction techniques did not yield better results
 for this variable.
 Therefore, the FFDI computation did not use bias-corrected data for precipitati
on.
 However, the FFDI is less sensitive to changes in this variable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dowdy2009a"

\end_inset

.
 This weaker sensitivity might occur because the FFDI equation does not
 explicitly includes precipitation.
 This variable is part of the drought factor.
 This factor does not include precipitation explicitly either.
 The drought factor computation requires the calculation of moisture deficits.
 In this research, the use of the KBDI yields these deficits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bias-corrected seasonal FFDI computation (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the bias-correction, the magnitude of FFDI results is acceptable.
 However, the FFDI computed with reanalysis data slightly over-estimates
 seasonal fire weather.
 However, during most years, this over-estimation is not significant.
 Additionally, FFDI
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cum
\end_layout

\end_inset

 seems to be a better metric of seasonal fire weather than FFDI>25.
 The results with FFDIcum show a higher correlation between bushfire danger
 and activity.
 The result is consistent using weather station and alternative reanalysis
 data (see Chapter 6).
 This result is also similar using bias-corrected data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extended seasonal FFDI computation (1920-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is greater uncertainty in the accuracy of the results for the period
 1920-2010.
 Certain variables could present even larger biases before the period 1974-2010.
 The difference might be significant for variables like wind speed because
 of the incorporation of new technologies to measure this variable.
 Additionally, after the bias-correction the seasonal FFDI underestimates
 fire weather.
 This FFDI result is not consistent with the overestimation yielded for
 the period 1974-2010.
 There is no weather station data to compare the fields for the period 1920-1973.
 Therefore, an alternative approach could be the validation against an independe
nt reanalysis product like ERA-20C 
